0. Simple Web Stack Design

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com using a web browser.

The browser sends a request to a DNS server to resolve the domain name www.foobar.com.
The DNS returns the IP address 8.8.8.8, which is the IP of the server hosting the website.
The browser then sends an HTTP request to the server at 8.8.8.8.

The server is a physical or virtual machine that provides services to other computers.
In this infrastructure, a single server hosts all components of the web stack.

The domain name foobar.com allows users to access the website using a human readable name
instead of an IP address.

The www record in www.foobar.com is a DNS A record, which points the domain name to the
IPv4 address 8.8.8.8.

The web server (Nginx) receives HTTP requests from users, serves static content,
and forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

The application server runs the application code, processes business logic,
and communicates with the database when needed.

The database (MySQL) stores and manages persistent data such as user information
and application data.

The server communicates with the user's computer using HTTP or HTTPS over the TCP/IP protocol.

Issues with this infrastructure:

There is a single point of failure (SPOF) because everything runs on one server.
If the server goes down, the entire website becomes unavailable.

Maintenance or deployment requires restarting services, which causes downtime.

The infrastructure cannot scale because one server cannot handle a large amount of traffic.
